ANTHRAX, BOVINE - ARGENTINA (04): CONSEQUENCES
**********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: 26 Jun 2008
From: Merritt Clifton <anmlpepl@whidbey.com>


Just by way of background, I'm receiving reports lately that the
present Argentine economic crisis has hit the rural and ranching
sectors especially hard, and cattle herd caretaking is among the
casualties.

Rising fuel prices were apparently the trigger of the crisis. Since
the gauchos mostly traded their horses for motor vehicles long ago,
and since following herds burns fuel, vigilance against disease,
predation, rustling, etc. is down. Since cattle are not worth enough
at market to pay for their transport under present conditions, there is
less concern about losses than there was 6 months or a year ago.

I last heard about cases of herd neglect in Argentina probably 6-7
years ago, maybe longer. It isn't something the Argentine humane
community mentions often, so when it is mentioned, I tend to notice.

--
Merritt Clifton
Editor, Animal People
P.O. Box 960
Clinton, WA 98236
<http://www.animalpeoplenews.org>
<anmlpepl@whidbey.com>

